 about the professionalization and accreditation of the discipline itself. Some chapters merge thinking about child and youth care with esoteric and literary prose; others use humour and satire as a way to represent both foundational and entirely new directions in the field. With Children and Youth provides no set conclusions or findings about the field; instead, it guides the reader to spaces of controversy, contention, and opportunities for innovation and change. Child and youth care practice and theory, it is argued, is based fundamentally on engagement across generations, cultures, and social positions, and this book exemplifies precisely that.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial work with children. 0aSocial work with youth. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aPolitical Science: Social Policy. 4aPolitical Science: Social Services. 4aSocial Science: Child Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAnderson-Nathe, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFewster, Gerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGharabaghi, Kiaras, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGharabaghi, Kiaras, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKrueger, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrueger, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMagnuson, Doug, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewbury, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPacini-Ketchabaw, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhelan, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkott-Myhre, Hans A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/